  We examine how uncertainty about the relevance of third-party news ("external
signal") influences investor beliefs, market prices and corporate disclosures.
Despite assuming independence between signals' relevance and firms' information
endowment, we find that favorable external signals are taken ``with a grain of
salt" in equilibrium -- more precisely, perceived as less likely relevant --
which reinforces investor beliefs that the firms are endowed with unfavorable
information. As a result, more favorable external signals could paradoxically
lead to lower market valuation. In line with mounting empirical evidence, we
predict asymmetric price reactions to external news and price declines
following firm disclosures.
